- **Port parameter lacks bounds validation** `factory/cli.py:98`: The port option accepts any integer without validation. Valid TCP port range is 1–65535 (port 0 is reserved). Ports < 1024 require root/admin privileges and will cause permission errors. Ports > 65535 are invalid and will silently fail at uvicorn.run() time with cryptic error messages. Users need explicit validation at CLI argument parsing time, not at server startup.
- **Synchronous blocking server prevents concurrent CLI operation** `factory/cli.py:106`: uvicorn.run() is a blocking call that acquires the event loop indefinitely. This prevents any other CLI commands from executing while the server is running. The factory tool is designed for orchestrating remote tasks, but this architecture forces users to choose between running the HTTP server OR running CLI commands in the same session. This violates the separation of concerns—the CLI should remain responsive and capable of spawning other operations while the server runs in background.
- **Host parameter accepts any string; no validation for IP/hostname format** `factory/cli.py:97`: The host parameter at line 97 is declared as `str = typer.Option("127.0.0.1", "--host", "-h", help="Host to bind to")` with no validation. Users can pass arbitrary strings (e.g., `--host ';;;;'`, `--host ../../../etc/passwd`, or invalid IPs like `256.256.256.256`) which will silently fail at runtime when uvicorn attempts to bind. No validation-time feedback is provided.
