        "body": "**subprocess.run() is blocking; misleading comment about CLI responsiveness**\n\nThe subprocess.run() call with check=True blocks at the Python level until uvicorn exits. The docstring claims 'keeping the CLI responsive' but this is incorrect—the Python process is blocked and cannot accept other commands until the server terminates. To truly keep CLI responsive, you would need subprocess.Popen() without wait(), daemon process spawning, or explicit background execution. The current implementation provides false confidence about architecture.\n\nRaised by: claude-code\n\nSuggested fix: Use subprocess.Popen() for true background execution: `proc = subprocess.Popen([sys.executable, '-m', 'uvicorn', ...])` without calling wait(). Or add a --daemon flag that spawns in background and exits the CLI immediately. Document the architectural trade-off clearly.",
